boot: Increase menu timeout and ESC delay for slow-display compatibility

Extend the default boot menu wait time to 9 seconds and the ESC key
acceptance delay to 3 seconds. These adjustments accommodate systems with
slow display initialization, ensuring the menu is fully visible before
timeout or accidental dismissal. The longer delays prevent users from
missing the prompt on sluggish screens and reduce the risk of unintended
boots caused by habitual key mashing during the display warm-up period.

Signed-off-by: Mike Banon <mikebdp2@gmail.com>
---
 src/boot.c | 7 ++++---
 1 file changed, 4 insertions(+), 3 deletions(-)

diff --git a/src/boot.c b/src/boot.c
index 0a4324cc..1800dc7a 100644
--- a/src/boot.c
+++ b/src/boot.c
@@ -744,7 +744,8 @@ get_keystroke(int msec)
 
 int BootSequence VARLOW = -1;
 
-#define DEFAULT_BOOTMENU_WAIT 2500
+#define DEFAULT_BOOTMENU_WAIT 9000
+#define ESC_ACCEPTED_TIME     3000
 
 static const char keyboard_keys[] = {
     '1','2','3','4','5','6','7','8','9','0',
@@ -1076,10 +1077,10 @@ interactive_bootmenu(void)
     print_bootmenu_page(entries, page_start, page_end, paging_enabled, page_num);
 
     // Get key press.  If the menu key is ESC, do not restart boot unless
-    // 1.5 seconds have passed.  Otherwise users (trained by years of
+    // three seconds have passed.  Otherwise users (trained by years of
     // repeatedly hitting keys to enter the BIOS) will end up hitting ESC
     // multiple times and immediately booting the primary boot device.
-    int esc_accepted_time = irqtimer_calc(menukey == 1 ? 1500 : 0);
+    int esc_accepted_time = irqtimer_calc(menukey == 1 ? ESC_ACCEPTED_TIME : 0);
     for (;;) {
         clear_keyboard_buffer();
         keystroke = get_keystroke_full(1000);
